text: She could be a scientist. she could totally be a scientist who discovered the cure for cancer. But she isn't, that's not the way the film makers wanted the film to go. That completely changes the whole genre of the film. And don't get me wrong, I love science fiction, I ADORE IT actually. But I am sick and tired of people equating every little thing to feminism. They had an opportunity but obviously the writers didn't want this to become a scifi movie. Which is completely ok with me. And that is because it's still interesting, I think the plot, albeit not original,is beautiful. So yes hopefully someday someone will make a bad ass, strong but weak, riveting, complex, and immortal woman that finds the cure for cancer and her team of scientists are mostly women. But this film isn't it, and it does't deserve hate for being something that it's not.

text: LOOL god some of you are so low and so unappreciative of creative works. Instead of giving praises, views or constructive criticisms, you're just hating on it and commenting such unrelated, out of context bullshit. Who care's if in all that time that she didn't find a cure for cancer? Maybe science wasn't her forte? No matter how long she lives she'd still need qualifications and knowledge of the subject to actually do anything and progress on it. I for sure know that if I didn't age, I wouldn't be finding a cure for cancer - simply because I hate science and I know nothing about it.  The girl's just trying to live her life and make do with what her situation because essentially..she's alone in the world. All those connections and bonds that she's made throughout her life will all fade out in time and she'll be left with all of the memories, all by herself.  Also, I'm pretty sure you haters didn't expect a plot line of someone that can cure cancer because she didn't age, when you clicked on the title to watch this trailer.   P.S. text: Finally an adult female acting like an adult female. The story is ridiculous of course but the actress blake somebody at least knows how to act. She is appropriately sad and the continuing generations of the same dog thing really does deserve some recognition, like a ballpeen hammer in the phrenologist's heavy hand. Come on, like the story and the good actress couldn't carry the weight? So this putzy and ditzy character is a hundred plus and hasn't discovered much about human nature. She should be in an isolated valley running human hunting trips. I can't think of a man or woman that wouldn't be that way after a century. After a whole century she's still such a victim! That steams me and now I wanna shit on someone's car and eat their rose bushes. Can you believe that harrison actually thought he could act? Thankfully I can't get my hoof down my throat or I'd be yakking up my third stomach. Adaline and her daughter do MAKE the movie. The throwaway other characters are worthless and pointless and a waste of time. The story could have been a revelation instead of a maudlin retelling of the american victimization story. Because if a rich white woman can still hit the high hard one after a century, she sure as hell wouldn't be playing the perennial victim. The film isn't much but Blake, written though it were, played the understated victim to a T, and she did a bangup jobbie.

text: Spoilers: Adaline went to a Car Crash back in 1935, she crashed in the water and died but the lighting strike striked the vechile. She was actually dead but the lighting saved her. When year pass by Adaline's daughter was all grown up. She even look like a sister. Later in one day a police officer pulled her over and was checking her lincese. The police officer got suspicious that she was born on 1908 and she doesn't look that old. The government got curious and they wanted to do experiments on her, you know because she's one of a kind and a specimen. She went back to San Fransico to learn her condition. There were no answers at all. Later when she was going back to her car, 2 police took her to they car. The government is even curious than usual. She didn't wanna be tested, she wanted to be free, so she escape out the car. After a few days, Adaline met her daughter and told her that she wasn't aging properly, she said she must keep moving and don't get caught by the police.

text: I ran into this while browsing for a movie to watch and I was reminded of how disappointing the plot was. They had so many options they could have played with, but they didn't. They stuck with this kinda weird romance plot. The story could have been so much more interesting, I would have liked to have seen more situations she went through, throughout the time periods. She can't age, so use that and show us years worth of what she saw! Not just fancy dresses and romance. *Some* romance (and fancy dresses) would've been nice, like the agony she had over relationships lost and what she liked about each of them (a dress for each decade? Yes please.). Also, cut the thunder snow explanation, leave it ambiguous, she doesn't age because... reasons (groundhog day). I don't hate this movie, I just see it as a missed opportunity. Also, this comment is much longer than I intended.

text: The trouble of gerontologists is that they do not investigate the destruction of the human body, instead they examine the cell's body, therefore, they cannot understand anything. If you look in the encyclopedia, you will not find a kinship between the two organisms - human and cell. It is, but biologists do not know it. Therefore, everyone dies. 100 years ago, researchers L. Woodruff, A. Carrol, S Metalnikov experimentally determined that the cell has no mechanisms of aging, the process of interaction with the surrounding nutrient medium kills the cell. The human body that has grown out of this cell also has no mechanisms for aging. What do biologists have been looking for for decades?
